[normal]Written evidence submitted by Circle Housing Croup[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1. [bold]About Circle Housing Group[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1.1 
[normal]Circle is one of the 
[normal]UK
[normal]’s leading providers of affordable housing. With a dedicated team of more than 2,200 staff, Circle manages 65,000 homes, including supported and sheltered housing, for around 200,000 people across the 
[normal]UK
[normal]. Its mission is to enhance the life chances of its r
[normal]esidents by providing great homes and reliable services, and building sustainable communities.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.2 Circle 
[normal]Housing 
[normal]G
[normal]roup includes 12 partners. Nine registered providers (RPs): South Anglia Housing, Wherry Housing Association, Old Ford Housing Association, 
[normal]Circle 33 Housing Trust, Merton Priory Homes, Mole Valley Housing Association, Mercian Housing Association, Roddons Housing Association and Russet Homes; two support &amp; care partners: Circle Support and Invicta Telecare, as well as Circle Living for sales a
[normal]nd marketing and management of shared ownership, market rent and private sale properties, and property repairs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3 Across the Group, 
[normal]32% of 
[normal]our 
[normal]tenants receive full Housing Benefit and 27% receive partial Housing Benefit. 
[normal]3
[normal],
[normal]3
[normal]99 of our customers are affec
[normal]ted by the Under-Occupation Penalty (also known as the ‘Bedroom Tax’
[normal])
[normal] and 
[normal]197 are affected by the Benefit
[normal] Cap.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2. [bold]New and innovative responses to the changes to housing support [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Mutual Exchange
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1
[normal] 
[normal]Circle 
[normal]Housing Group provides House Exchange, the country’s largest not-for-profit web-based mutual exchange service. 
[normal]House Exchange allows for home swaps between 
[normal]any council and housing association tenant with the right to mutually exchange by
[normal] automatically matc
[normal]hing house-seekers with 
[normal]a home
[normal] that meet their needs. There are 300,000 people registered on the site and more than 220,000 properties on the system.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2 Mutual exchange can be a useful tool in responding to welfare reform by enabling tenants to move to a
[normal] property which is cheaper to run or which has fewer bedrooms 
[normal]and therefore avoids the Under-O
[normal]ccupation Penalty.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3
[normal] Indeed, since the Under-O
[normal]ccupation Penalty was introduced in April 2013, the number of registrations to House Exchange website, 
[normal]www.houseexchange.org.uk
[normal], have increased by 26%. The majority of those registering on the site, around 26%, are looking to move to a larger property 
[normal]but 
[normal]the number looking to down
[normal]-size
[normal] has increased as a proportion of registrations to around 10%.
[normal] We have also held 
[normal]successful ‘speed-dating’ events where we invite
[normal] tenants 
[normal]to attend and try to 
[normal]find a 
[normal]suitable 
[normal]property match for mutual exchange.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Investment in Financial Inclusion
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4 
[normal]C
[normal]ircle Housing Group invest
[normal]s
[normal] £1m 
[normal]each year 
[normal]in financial inclusion services
[normal] 
[normal]in three main areas. Firstly, we provide health checks, to support customers to understand their finances and know what support is available such as money advice and 
[normal]our 
[normal]benefits ca
[normal]lculator.
[normal] 
[normal]Secondly, we focus on prevention by supporting customers to proactively manage their finances and maximise effective use of services and products such as bank accounts and affordable credit. Finally, in crisis situations, we 
[normal]give
[normal] 
[normal]customers 
[normal]access
[normal] 
[normal]to specialised 
[normal]support services such as debt advice
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5 
[normal]O
[normal]ne of our partners, Roddons Housing Association, 
[normal]has 
[normal]also secured £1m funding over 5 years from the Big Lottery Fund’s ‘Improving Financial Confidence’ programme which has funded additional staff
[normal] an
[normal]d training in our income team. 
[normal]Across the Group, our
[normal] income officers
[normal] have
[normal] reprioritised the use of resources to ensure a focus on face-to-face communication with tenants impacted by the Under-Occupation Penalty and 
[normal]the Benefit
[normal] 
[normal]Cap 
[normal]through a programme of
[normal] home visits.
[normal] 
[normal]As a result of this investment, our arrears level have so far been held at a steady level, 
[normal]and in fact reduced
[normal] f
[normal]rom 3.2% in July 2012 to 3.1% in
[normal] July 2013. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Employment and Skills Support
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.6
[normal] 
[normal]We believe that getting people into employment 
[normal]and training is a crucial tool
[normal] help 
[normal]to 
[normal]address the welfare reform challenge. Last year, we helped 9
[normal],
[normal]417 people with employment and skills support, including 1
[normal],
[normal]934 into paid work, accredited training or apprenticeships. We are also the lead partner in a pan
[normal]-London shared apprenticeship scheme in partnership with the CITB to support the movement of apprentices between contractors to ensure that they can complete their training.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.7
[normal] As part of our £1.2 billion repairs and maintenance procurement, each contrac
[normal]tor will provide one apprenticeship opportunity within their business for every £0.5m that Circle spends with them. This means 233 apprenticeship opportunities will be created over the 10-year lifespan of the new contracts. In addition, our contractors wil
[normal]l offer 77 graduate placements or internships, 309 work placements and 166 volunteering opportunities within their businesses.
[normal] We would like to see other organisations take a similar pro-active approach to apprenticeships in their procurement projects.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]En
[normal]ergy and Warm Homes
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.8
[normal] Circle is also working to save tenants money on their energy bills
[normal],
[normal] securing £200,000 through DECC’s Renewable Heat Premium Payment scheme to install air source heat pumps and 
[normal]last year we installed measures that helped our custome
[normal]rs save around £450,000 on their energy bills.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.9 We have around 60 Resident Energy Champions across the Group. Since their initial training session in April last year, the Champions have passed on energy saving advice to over 250 Circle customers with a
[normal]n expected saving for each customer of around £100 per year through following basic energy saving tips.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.10 We have partnered with the National Housing Federation to provide an energy tariff switching service bespoke to Circle staff and customers, provid
[normal]ing a service they can trust to find a cheaper deal on their energy bills. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Social Return on Investment
[normal] (SROI) and Wellbeing valuation
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.11
[normal] 
[normal]Overall 
[normal]Circle
[normal] invests £3 million a year in sustainable communities activities, and 
[normal]delivers
[normal] a return of £31.8 million in value obtained in kind through projects, value obtained in external funding and total returned value based on currently valuable interventions. This included £16.8 million value from Employment and Skills outcomes and £13.7 mi
[normal]llion value from Financial Inclusion outcomes. 
