[normal]3[bold]. [bold]The implications of the changes for landlords[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Impact on capacity to build new homes
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1 Circle’s intention is to develop a substantial number of new homes in the years to come, and under our current
[normal] financial plan
[normal] we have the capacity to do so.
[normal] We 
[normal]therefore 
[normal]welcome the recent rent regime settlement for the 10 years from 2015/16, providing a level of stabi
[normal]lity on our main income stream.
[normal] However, we may be compelled to revisit our assumptions if curren
[normal]t uncertainties surrounding key elements of Welfare Reform (particularly Universal Credit roll-out and the new welfare cap arrangements) 
[normal]result in
[normal] a further increase in costs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Impact of Under-Occupation Penalty
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2 For tenancy sustainment services, the U
[normal]nder-Occupation Penalty has affected 20-30% of households and assistance is being provided to facilitate moves to more appropriately sized accommodation. The main impact already being seen in regard to tenant custome
[normal]r behaviour in response to the Under-Occ
[normal]upation P
[normal]enalty is a significant escalation in the rate of enquiries and completions of mutual exchanges of tenancy.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3 
[normal]When offering an internal transfer to a new home within our properties to one of our existing tenants, we will currently maintain thei
[normal]r rent level at social rent
[normal], rather than moving them onto Affordable R
[normal]ent. However, due
[normal] to the higher number of internal transfers as a result of needing to find accommodation for tenants affected by the Under-Occupation Penalty, this has resulted in 
[normal]fewer
[normal] conversions to Affordable Rent as part of the Affordable Homes Programme
[normal]. Because the programme is designed to use this increase in rental income
[normal] 
[normal]from conversions to fund the building of new homes, this has had a negative effect on our 
[normal]capacity which we h
[normal]ave had to fu
[normal]nd from elsewhere.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4 
[normal]There is also potential for programme delivery disruption as local authority planning c
[normal]ommittee m
[normal]embers seeking to substantially amend schemes in order to include numbers of smal
[normal]ler units as a response to the Under-Occu
[normal]pation P
[normal]enalty – which may render some schemes as financially non-viable or, even if this is not the case, at a minimum substantially slow
[normal]er 
[normal]delivery timescales.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Impact of Benefit Cap
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5
[normal] 
[normal]We have also have seen sizable decreases in income for customers as a result of 
[normal]the Benefit Cap
[normal], although these are small in number. Reductions have been in the region of £100 - £150 a month outside of 
[normal]London
[normal] and £240 within 
[normal]London
[normal]. 
[normal]However, we have one fa
[normal]mily in 
[normal]London
[normal] which is losing £330 a week under the measure. 
[normal]It is likely that rent payments will be the key area where families amend their budgets and this in turn may prevent their move to smaller accommodation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Impact of Universal Credit and Direct P
[normal]ayments
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.6
[normal] 
[normal]This measure is by far the greatest risk to our revenue stream and future financial resources available for investment in housing and provision of community services. 
[normal]Any significant increase in arrears levels
[normal] 
[normal]would
[normal] have a
[normal]n
[normal] impact on
[normal] housing a
[normal]ssociations’ cash flow and revenue position and 
[normal]the capacity of association
[normal]s
[normal] to build new homes and invest in local services.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.7 The uncertainty around 
[normal]the implementation and timetable for 
[normal]Universal Credit 
[normal]has made it very difficult for housing associa
[normal]tions to conduct their business planning and to make any realistic consideration of additional resources required to support our customers with Universal Credit in the absence of a firm, clear and detailed national roll-out plan. We are working with the De
[normal]partment of Work and Pensions to establish the detail of how Universal Credit will operate but as an organisation which operates over 127 local authority areas it would be useful to have 
[normal]know as early 
[normal]as possible where Universal Credit will next be 
[normal]impleme
[normal]nted as part of the national roll-out
[normal] so that we can manage our resources accordingly.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.8 
[normal]As a result of the impact of Universal Credit and direct payments, housing associations may be forced to re
[normal]view their allocations policy and risk manage and profile
[normal] their future lettings by focussing on people in work who will have greater ability to pay and less dependency on welfare benefits. 
[normal]This would have a significant impact on the resources of local authorities who would be responsible for housing more people 
[normal]on full Housing Benefit.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4[bold]. [bold]The implications of the changes for claimants[bold] and vulnerable people[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1 
[normal]In 2011, in preparation for welfare reform we undertook a survey of our tenants and their attitudes to their finances. It 
[normal]led to
[normal] the following findings:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal] 
[normal]The report 
[normal]showed
[normal] that our tenants will need more advice to help them respond when the Government brings together all benefits under the Universal Credit
[normal] and recipients 
[normal]receive all of their benefits in one ‘monthly lump sum’ to their accounts for 
[normal]the first time ever, rather than their rent being paid direct to their landlord.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3 
[normal]Most of our tenants will not be used to receiving this amount of money at once, and may have difficulties in the transition to the new system. Some will want support to h
[normal]elp them understand the changes and manage their money. 
[normal]The movement to monthly budgeting will be a challenge for households with the likelihood of shortfalls in the various household budgets will require additional assistance, most notably budgeting for f
[normal]ood and u
[normal]tility costs if paid via a pre-
[normal]payment meter system. 
[normal]The DWP is keen for these direct payments to be made online and for advice to be internet-based. However, our research shows that 45% of our customers don’t have internet access at home, and can
[normal]’t access online advice. So, for many, online solutions will not work, and face-to-face advice is the most effective way to guide people through the changes. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4 In July 2013 we did a further survey of our customers which showed that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This shows the lack of awareness amongst social housing tenants towards Universal Credit and its implications and the challenge faced by housing 
[normal]associations to prepare people for direct payments and the need to budget monthly to cover rent and other basic requirements.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5 In t
[normal]he light of this, our recommendation is that the Government should provide a guarantee of at least one face-to-face money
[normal] advice session for each new recipient of direct Universal Credit payments who needs it. In this way, we can prepare people for the 
[normal]transition to the new welfare reform system
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]give them the information and guidance they need to navigate towards proacti
[normal]ve management of their resources.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]5[bold]. [bold]The treatment of housing costs within Universal Credit[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1 We would like to see the
[normal] housing element 
[normal]of Universal Credit 
[normal]to be clearly defined and not 
[normal]just absorbed within with the single payment to allow those who 
[normal]wish to have their housing costs deducted at source to be able to do so.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2 
[normal]There are also some 
[normal]practical
[normal] questions around how the housing cost element will work in practice. 
[normal]If ‘direct payments’ to the tenant are switched back to ‘managed payments’ to t
[normal]he landlord after 8 weeks of arrears as suggested by the Department for Work and Pensions, it is not clear how this debt will be recovered through the benefits system and how the need to reduce these arrears will be balanced against the tenants need to pay
[normal] for basic goods such as food and heating. Clarity from Government is required in this area and we are keen to work with the Department and others to ensure both the wellbeing of our customers and the financial stability of the housing association sector.
